mes © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"la","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Hung, Cuong, Anh, Thanh, Ha, Hoang, Tuan, Chau, Hao, Hien, Hoa, Hue, Nam, Phong, Sinh, Tuong, Min, Tam, Tanh, Thai, Tham, Tinh, Yeong.  Chinese Hong, Hang, Sang, Tong, Chan, Chi, Hwa Ja, Hyung, Kam, Ki Bong, Kin, Man.","Vietnamese: from the Chinese surname 羅, see   Luo   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Lã</b>): from the Chinese surname 呂, see   Lu   6 and 3 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Luo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Jian, Yi, Ping, Yong, Zhen, Feng, Hong, Ming, Jin, Bin, Chen, Hai, Lan, Min, Huan, Hung, Shen, Tian.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 羅, meaning ‘net for catching birds’ or ‘to collect’ in Chinese: (i) from Luo (羅), the name of an ancient state (located in present-day Hubei province). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the early Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ), people from the state migrated southwards and adopted Luo (羅) as their surname. (ii) from the Po Duo Luo (破多羅) and Chi Luo (叱羅) families from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China, who changed their original surnames to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) from the personal name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅), leader of an ancient Turkic tribe who are believed to have migrated to China during the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD ). His descendants inherited his name Hu Se Luo (斛瑟羅) as their surname and shortened it to 羅 during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) from the name of one of the seven families from the Bandun Man, an ethnic group residing in ancient southwestern China (located mainly in present-day Sichuan province)."]}]},{"name":"Barre","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Anatole, Emile, Pierre, Alphonse, Andre, Cecile, Henri, Herve, Jacques, Marcel, Regean, Yves.","French: topographic name for someone who lived by a gateway or barrier, or in a house encircled by a fence, from Old French <i>barre</i> ‘bar, obstruction’ (of obscure origin, possibly akin to the Celtic element <i>barr</i> ‘height’); or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, e.g. Barre-en-Ouche in Eure or Barre-de-Semilly in Manche. Compare   Labarre  .","French: probably also a habitational name from Barre in Lozère, named with the Celtic element <i>barr</i> ‘height’."],"variants":[{"name":"Labarre","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Alain, Andre, Armand, Aurore, Fernande, Gilles, Herve, Laure, Michel, Urbain.","French: topographic name for someone who lived by a gateway or barrier, or in a house encircled by a fence, from Old French <i>barre</i> ‘bar, obstruction’ (see   Barre   1), with fused feminine definite article <i>la</i>; or a habitational name from any of various places called with this word, e.g. Barre-en-Ouche in Eure or Barre-de-Semilly in Manche. Compare   Labar  ,   Labare  ,   Labarr  ,   Labor  ,   Labore  ,   Lebar  , and   Lebarre  .","History: In North America, this surname was originally also a secondary surname or <i>dit</i> (‘also called’) name, borne by Jacques Genest or Genet <i>dit</i> Labarre from France (see   Genest  )."]},{"name":"Baray","meanings":["Hispanic (Mexico): unexplained.","In some cases possibly also French: variant of <b>Barray</b>, itself a variant of <b>Barrey</b>, a derivative of   Barre   1. In France, it is found mainly in Seine-Maritime."]},{"name":"Barrere","meanings":["French (<b>Barrère</b>): topographic name for someone who lived by a gate or barrier, or a metonymic occupational name for a gatekeeper, from a derivative of Old French <i>bar(r)e</i> ‘bar, rod’, in the sense of ‘barrier’ (compare   Barre   1); or a habitational name from (La) Barrère, the name of several places in the southwestern part of France.","English: variant of <b>Barrer</b>, for someone who lived by a town or castle gate, from Middle English <i>barre</i> ‘barrier, gateway’. Compare above and   Barr   4."]},{"name":"Barriere","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Gaston, Monique, Philippe.","French (<b>Barrière</b>): topographic name for someone who lived by a gate or barrier, or a metonymic occupational name for a gatekeeper, from a derivative of Old French <i>bar(r)e</i> ‘bar, rod’, in the sense of ‘barrier’ (compare   Barre   1); or a habitational name from (La) Barrière, the name of several places in various parts of France. Compare   Gates  ."]},{"name":"Barreau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Fresnel, Gabrielle, Jean-Louis, Jean-Marie, Jeanty, Michel, Michelene, Pierre.","French:","derivative of Old French <i>bar(r)e</i> ‘bar, rod’, in the sense of ‘barrier’ (compare   Barre   1), hence a nickname for a fence keeper or a topographic name for someone who lived in a house encircled by a fence."]},{"name":"Barrier","meanings":["French: occupational name for a gatekeeper, from Old French <i>barier</i>, an agent derivative of <i>bar(r)e</i> ‘bar, rod’, in the sense of ‘barrier’ (compare   Barre   1).","Altered form of French   Barriere  .","Altered form of German   Berger  ."]},{"name":"Barra","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Marina, Antonio, Augusto, Biagio, Carlo, Domenic, Flavio, Gennaro, Lorenzo, Luciano, Rocco, Salvatore.  Spanish Jorge, Carlos, Diego, Enrique, Jaime, Juan, Manuel.","Italian (southern), Spanish, and Portuguese: topographic name from <i>barra</i> ‘bar, rod’ (in the sense of ‘barrier, sandbank’), or a habitational name from any of the places called with this word.","French (southern): dialect variant of   Barre   1."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":0,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":35,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":66,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":91,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":104,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"de la